## What happened

In .NET 11, **DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) was removed from macOS**. Calling `DSA.Create()` now throws at runtime on macOS. Windows and Linux are unaffected.

## How to fix

Since you're **verifying legacy signatures** (read-only), you have two options:

**Option A ŌĆö Platform-guard DSA (keep legacy verification on Windows/Linux only):**
```csharp
if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException("DSA verification unavailable on macOS");

using var dsa = DSA.Create();
dsa.ImportParameters(legacyPublicKey);
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

**Option B ŌĆö Migrate to ECDSA/RSA (recommended long-term):**
Re-sign existing artifacts with a modern algorithm, then verify with:
```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create();
ecdsa.ImportSubjectPublicKeyInfo(publicKey, out _);
bool valid = ecdsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

If you truly need cross-platform legacy DSA verification and cannot re-sign, consider using a third-party library (e.g., Bouncy Castle) that provides a managed DSA implementation independent of the OS.
